[start section id="20103"]

Mr. Harris is a pleasant 51-year-old gentleman who has been relatively healthy aside from the below issues.
#1 Presumed rectal adenocarcinoma
He was in his usual state of health until approximately three weeks ago when he began to note maroon to bright-red blood per rectum.  This was often not mixed in with stool.  He began to pass frequent bloody, mucousy stools.  He initially attributed this to hemorrhoids.  However, after three weeks he sought further evaluation by his local physicians.  On May 3, 2010, a colonoscopy was performed (this was his first screening colonoscopy).  It noted a mass 10-cm from the anal verge.  It was approximately 5-cm in length and a diameter of 30-mm.  The scope was able to be passed through the lesion and reach the ileocecal valve without difficulty.  The pathology specimen has been sent here and is pending review, but per outside report, it did confirm adenocarcinoma.  He denied any additional symptoms at that time including abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, constipation, diarrhea, or change in his stool caliber.  He denies any weight-loss as well.  A CT-scan of his abdomen and pelvis was performed and was notable for a 5.8- x 4.1-cm mass on his left kidney that was concerning for renal cell carcinoma.  In addition, his left adrenal gland was enlarged at 1.4-cm.  The radiology report from the outside facility did not comment on enhancement.  Also, there was some thickening of the bowel wall near the rectum but no evidence of invasion to the side wall or adjacent structures.

[end section id="20103"]

